One thing I know for sure, high-end luxury interior design clients love knowing exactly what this project is going to cost at the front end of the project. ⁠
⁠
When I hear from designers, “but I’m afraid that number is going to scare them away.”, the truth is... if it does scare them away and it IS in fact the real number it’s going to take to do this project, then it’s a beautiful thing that you found out BEFORE you signed them on as a client and got six months into the project... right??⁠
⁠
When we give our clients as much information to empower them to make a reasonable and sound decision that they are thrilled with all the way through the project, we’ve done them a great service and we’ve given ourselves the ability to have a full roster of only clients that absolutely value us and can afford our services all the way to the end of the project. ⁠
⁠

You know I love layers and layers of textures and lighting in my designs. The same goes for my client communication. ⁠
⁠
Layers of communication are key to establishing a great rapport with all of my clients. Stick to your preferred means of communication (mine: in-person meetings or emails), but mimic your client's preferred communication style as well (if they are a phone person, leave them a polite and upbeat voicemail after putting it in writing).⁠
⁠
What’s your preferred method of communication? ⁠

📷 @markweinbergnyc

Communication style — what’s yours?⁠
⁠
I always tell my clients up front that I’m an in-person meeting and email kind of gal. I don’t love the phone...never have. Not even in my teen years.⁠
⁠
Whatever your communication style, it’s important that it be consistent.⁠
⁠
Our client communication is branded and consistent from every angle. For example:⁠

- Potential call with our team⁠

I used to think that every design project was different. That I couldn’t possibly systematize the crazy ride that is interior design.⁠⁠

I decided that I was done with the people-pleasing and defined the project structure that worked best for my firm. It not only worked...it soared. I had so much success with this more clearly defined model (clients LOVE clarity), that I kept the new and improved outlook going. If words like AP, AR, WIP and income statement make your head spin, it’s time to outsource your finances and accounting to a professional. ⁠

⁠If you’re at all out of your depth with your numbers, this is the first hire you make. But, you have to stay present!⁠

You’re going to raise your rates when you are in high demand - you’ve got more potential client conversations going than you could possibly take on. If you are signing every single person that you pitch and every single person is signing on the dotted line and saying, “absolutely, yes… let’s start that job.” You may consider raising your rates. ⁠
⁠
My husband always says to me if you don’t get a few people telling you, “I can’t afford that you’re too expensive, that’s out of my budget, that’s more than I was expecting.”... then you’re probably not pushing the limit on your rates, right? The old adage is, if you sign everybody, you’re probably charging too little. You need to find that balance where you are signing some amazing projects but you’re also not for everyone… you’re not priced for each and every person.⁠
⁠
In addition, if you are delivering top-notch, killer designs… if you are like me and you finally get happy with it and it’s finally all clicking into place and you are giddy with excitement and you can not wait to show your clients the designs you put together you’re getting somewhere… you’ve got it, you’ve got the eye, you’ve got the talent, you’ve got the resources, you have the vendors you know all the trades, you know where to shop this, you know where to have something custom made… if you can feel it all clicking and you are presenting to your clients and they are eating it up they are loving it they are, “yes, yes, yes… let’s get this going.” Then you are in that sweet spot.⁠
⁠
If it’s time to get office space. If it’s time to add an employee. If it’s time to put more money in your pocket because you are working your booty off. Those are ALL  good reasons to consider raising your rates. ⁠

Knowing that we’ve built this extraordinary life with two undergraduate degrees from Michigan State, and an upbringing without scarcity or overindulgence, I’ve had faith that I will always have enough. It’s been proven to me too many times to have any doubt.

Having done a ton of business and spiritual coaching, I realize this lack of fear around finances is such a gift. It’s that faith in abundance and appreciation for all that I have that draws more and more abundance to me.

You pick your price. You set your price. And I don’t care what happens, you NEVER waiver.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And if you tell yourself that there is ANY wiggle room, you WILL wiggle. And if you wiggle in the beginning of a relationship you become negotiable throughout the ENTIRE relationship.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I’ve heard this a thousand times when I’ve asked for a recommendation. I say, “Do you have a good x, y, z?” and they say “Oh, sure and hey, just so you know... their pricing is negotiable so make sure you give a little push.”⁠⁠
⁠⁠
IF you negotiate, not only are you opening yourself up to being negotiable to that ONE client, but your referral base also knows to push on you. They know you have wiggle room in your pricing. ⁠
